---
import Atlas from '@/layouts/Atlas.astro';
import { getInventory, getAllPackages } from '@/lib/atlas';

const inv = await getInventory();
const pkgs = await getAllPackages();
const ch = inv.chapters.find(c => c.id === '07')!;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const sdkCore = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'sdk-core')!;
const sdkRs   = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'sdk-rs')!;
const nodeSdk = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'node-sdk')!;
const webSdk  = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'web-sdk')!;
---
<Atlas chapter="07" title={ch.title} crumb={`07 · ${ch.title}`}>
  <article class="prose" style="padding: 56px 64px; max-width: 1100px;">
    <div class="label">chapter 07 · {ch.read} · voice: {ch.voice}</div>
    <h1 style="margin-top: 14px;">protocol <span class="squig">version handshake</span></h1>

    <p>
      The SDK and the tinycloud node are versioned independently — the
      SDK ships on npm at <code>{inv.repo.version}</code>, the node ships
      a Rust binary on its own cadence. They have to agree on a wire
      protocol before a session is worth anything. That agreement is one
      integer.
    </p>

    <p>
      <code>checkNodeInfo</code> in
      <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/pkg/sdk-core/`}>{sdkCore.npm}</a>
      is the handshake. It runs at sign-in time, inside
      <code>NodeUserAuthorization</code> on the node-sdk side and the
      equivalent on the web-sdk side, before any session is built.
    </p>

    <h2>the wire</h2>

    <div class="mermaid-wrap" style="margin: 24px 0; padding: 24px; position: relative;">
      <span class="cap">handshake.svg</span>

      <div class="row gap-16 between" style="align-items: flex-start;">
        <div class="card" style="flex: 1; padding: 14px 16px;">
          <div class="label">SDK</div>
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 12px; margin-top: 6px;">wasm.protocolVersion()</div>
          <div style="font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-2); margin-top: 8px;">
            Rust kernel exposes the integer through the WASM seam. The
            JS-side bindings (<code>BrowserWasmBindings</code>,
            <code>NodeWasmBindings</code>) re-export it as
            <code>protocolVersion()</code>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="padding-top: 40px; min-width: 180px;">
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 11px; color: var(--ink-3); text-align: center;">GET /info</div>
          <svg width="180" height="40">
            <defs>
              <marker id="ah-r" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto">
                <path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="var(--accent)" />
              </marker>
              <marker id="ah-l" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="1" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
                <path d="M10,0 L0,5 L10,10 z" fill="var(--accent)" />
              </marker>
            </defs>
            <line x1="10" y1="14" x2="170" y2="14" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.4" marker-end="url(#ah-r)" />
            <line x1="170" y1="28" x2="10" y2="28" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.4" marker-end="url(#ah-l)" />
          </svg>
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 11px; color: var(--ink-3); text-align: center;">{ '{ protocol, version, features, quota_url }' }</div>
        </div>

        <div class="card" style="flex: 1; padding: 14px 16px;">
          <div class="label">node</div>
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 12px; margin-top: 6px;">/info endpoint</div>
          <div style="font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-2); margin-top: 8px;">
            Plain JSON. <code>protocol</code> is the integer the SDK has
            to match. <code>version</code> is the human-readable node
            version. <code>features</code> is a string array of optional
            capabilities. <code>quota_url</code> tells the SDK where to
            point users for upgrade flows.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout" style="bottom: 14px; right: 18px; transform: rotate(1.5deg); max-width: 220px;">
        equality. not range. not semver. integer equality.
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>what <code>checkNodeInfo</code> does</h2>

    <ol style="font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; padding-left: 24px;">
      <li><code>fetch(host + "/info")</code> with a 5 s <code>AbortSignal.timeout</code>. Network failure → <code>VersionCheckError</code>.</li>
      <li>Non-2xx response → <code>VersionCheckError</code>. There's no graceful skip — the SDK refuses to operate against an unreachable node.</li>
      <li>Compare <code>sdkProtocol !== data.protocol</code>. Strict integer mismatch → <code>ProtocolMismatchError</code> with both numbers, the node version, and the host. The error message tells the caller which side needs to update.</li>
      <li>Return <code>{ '{ features, quotaUrl }' }</code>. The features array is later consulted by <code>UnsupportedFeatureError</code> sites that want to advertise gracefully when a feature isn't supported.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>where it gets called</h2>

    <p>
      <code>NodeUserAuthorization</code> calls <code>checkNodeInfo(this.tinycloudHosts[0], this.wasm.protocolVersion())</code>
      twice during sign-in: once when establishing the session, and once
      when re-activating a host. Same on the web side. The pattern is:
      build the integer from the kernel, hand it to the resolver, fail
      hard on mismatch.
    </p>

    <div class="row gap-16" style="margin: 16px 0;">
      <a href={`${base}/pkg/sdk-core/`} class="card" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px; text-decoration: none; color: var(--ink);">
        <div class="label">resolver</div>
        <div class="mono" style="margin: 4px 0; font-size: 13px;">{sdkCore.npm}</div>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 13px;">
          <code>checkNodeInfo()</code>, <code>ProtocolMismatchError</code>,
          <code>VersionCheckError</code>, <code>UnsupportedFeatureError</code>,
          and the <code>NodeInfo</code> shape. {sdkCore.modules} modules ·
          {sdkCore.loc.toLocaleString()} loc.
        </p>
      </a>
      <a href={`${base}/pkg/sdk-rs/`} class="card" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px; text-decoration: none; color: var(--ink);">
        <div class="label">version source</div>
        <div class="mono" style="margin: 4px 0; font-size: 13px;">{sdkRs.npm}</div>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 13px;">
          The <code>protocolVersion</code> WASM export. Single integer
          baked into the Rust crate at compile time, surfaced through
          both web and node WASM packages.
        </p>
      </a>
    </div>

    <h2>what happens on mismatch</h2>

    <div class="card" style="padding: 14px 16px; margin: 16px 0; border-color: var(--accent);">
      <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">no graceful fallback</div>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 14px;">
        <code>ProtocolMismatchError</code> throws. It does not warn, it
        does not feature-flag down, it does not retry against an older
        endpoint. <code>sdkProtocol &lt; nodeProtocol</code> → message tells
        the caller to update the SDK.
        <code>sdkProtocol &gt; nodeProtocol</code> → message tells the operator
        to update the node. The error carries both integers, the
        node version string, and the host so callers can surface a
        useful upgrade prompt.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      Optional features are the soft-edged half. A node advertises them
      in <code>features[]</code>; the SDK calls
      <code>UnsupportedFeatureError</code> at use sites when the feature
      it wants isn't in the list. That error includes the available set
      so the caller can tell users what the node <em>does</em> support
      instead of just what it doesn't.
    </p>

    <h2>rolling out a new protocol version</h2>

    <p>
      The contract is: bump <code>protocolVersion</code> in the Rust
      crate <em>and</em> in tinycloud-node, in lockstep, and only when
      the wire format actually changes. Additive features go through the
      <code>features</code> array, not the protocol integer, so older
      SDKs keep working against newer nodes for non-breaking work.
    </p>

    <p>
      Operationally: a node operator who upgrades the node before the
      SDKs in the wild are updated will see clients fail with
      <code>ProtocolMismatchError</code> until they update. That's the
      design — it's louder than silent corruption, and the error message
      is explicit about who needs to act.
    </p>

    <h3>data this chapter reads</h3>
    <ul class="col gap-4">
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/inventory.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/sdk-core.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/sdk-rs.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/web-sdk.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/node-sdk.json</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>where to read next</h3>
    <p>
      Chapter <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/08/`}>08</a> drops down
      to the build topology — bun workspaces, turbo pipelines, and how
      <code>wasm-pack</code> produces the kernel that powers everything
      you've read so far.
    </p>
  </article>
</Atlas>
